    "body": "### Problem\n\n`nvim_buf_set_text` does not update `[` marker, I can't use `'[` to jump to previously changed text affected by `nvim_buf_set_text`, but press `u` correctly jump back to it.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n```lua\nvim.keymap.set(\"n\", \"<d-y>\", function()\n    local p = vim.fn.getpos(\"'[\")\n    local e = vim.fn.getpos(\"']\")\n    print(vim.inspect({ p[2], p[3], e[3] }))\nend)\nvim.keymap.set(\"n\", \"<d-o>\", function()\n    local row, col = unpack(vim.api.nvim_win_get_cursor(0))\n    vim.api.nvim_buf_set_text(0, row - 1, col, row - 1, col, { \"FF\" })\nend)\n```\nnvim --clean ~/.config/nvim/init.lua\npress `jj`\npress `<d-o>`\npress `<d-y>`, message shows they are `{1 , 1,  1}`\npress `'[`, cursor jump to line 1 col 0,\npress `u`, cursor jumps to line 3.\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe marker should reflect what's changed by `nvim_buf_set_text`, if it is not desired behavior, provide an api to query which position will it be after press u, this matters for multi-cursor undo implementation, plugin needs to reset each extmark (cursor) to the correct position, see https://github.com/jake-stewart/multicursor.nvim/issues/86.\nOne workaround may be using `wundo` to simulate undo in a different file to solely get it's cursor position, but it's not that  ideal.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.10.3\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nIt don't have the api\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nmacos 14.0\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nkitty\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm\n\n### Installation\n\nsource",
